child via homeschooling than she would get in a regular classroom. I feel very confident about it. &#10;Some teachers will not be your children's favorites and will be hard for them to deal with - that's a GOOD thing. Sometimes your children will be bored in school and want to act up or do something else but can't because they are in a classroom setting - again, a GOOD thing. These little things do lots in terms of preparing the special snowflakes for real life as well. &#10;While I agree that people who aren't my kids &quot;favorites&quot; and are &quot;hard for them to deal with&quot; is a good thing to learn to handle, and that boredom is a good thing to learn to handle, there is no reason that these lessons MUST be learned in a regular school setting. They can be learned equally as well (if not better) via other life experiences. &#10;Homeschooling isn't always a bad thing, but I definitely think that it should be a last chance kinda option not a first choice for well rounded children. &#10;I don't see any reason why a perfectly good homeschooling education should be a &quot;last choice.&quot;"/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1351" language="en" documentId="517" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="KRAMV" date="09/05/2013" docType="forumpost" origUrl="http://community.babycenter.com/post/a44369503/home_schooling_debate_this_hypothetical?cpg=14" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="517" notes="" title="Home schooling: Debate this hypothetical"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="138"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="139" end="382"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="383" end="754"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="755" end="1101"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="55" sofa="1" begin="1102" end="1256"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="59" sofa="1" begin="1257" end="1351"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47 51 55 